B044C014V018	44	14	18	Even by saying this they with difficulty kept the crowds from offering sacrifice to them.
B044C014V019	44	14	19	But Jews arrived from Antioch and Iconium and won over the crowds, and they stoned Paul and dragged him outside of the city, thinking that he was dead.
B044C014V020	44	14	20	But when the disciples gathered around him he rose up and reentered the city. On the next day he left with Barnabas for Derbe.
B044C014V021	44	14	21	Telling the good news in that city they made a number of disciples. Then they returned to Lystra and Iconium and Antioch,
B044C014V022	44	14	22	reassuring the minds of the disciples and encouraging them to be steadfast in the faith, saying, "Through many trials we must enter into the kingdom of God."
B044C014V023	44	14	23	They appointed elders for them in every church, and after prayer and fasting committed them to the Lord in whom they had believed.
B044C014V024	44	14	24	They passed through Pisidia and came into Pamphylia.
B044C014V025	44	14	25	After telling the message in Perga, they came down to Attalia.
B044C014V026	44	14	26	From there they sailed for Antioch, where they had been committed to the grace of God for the work which they had now completed.
B044C014V027	44	14	27	Upon their arrival they assembled the church and narrated all that God, working with them, had done, and how he had opened the door of faith to the Gentiles.
B044C014V028	44	14	28	There they passed no little time with the disciples.
B044C015V001	44	15	1	BUT certain men came down from Judaea and undertook to teach the brethren, "Unless you are circumcised according to the custom of Moses, you cannot be saved."
B044C015V002	44	15	2	Since no little dissension and controversy arose between Paul and Barnabas and these men, it was arranged that Paul and Barnabas and some others of them should go up to Jerusalem to the apostles and elders about this question.
B044C015V003	44	15	3	So they were sent on by the church and passed through Phoenicia and Samaria, relating the conversion of the Gentiles, which caused great joy to all the brethren.
B044C015V004	44	15	4	On their arrival in Jerusalem they were welcomed by the church and the apostles and the elders, and they narrated all that God, working with them, had done.
B044C015V005	44	15	5	Then some of the party of the Pharisees, who had become believers, rose and said, "We must circumcise them and tell them to keep the Law of Moses."
B044C015V006	44	15	6	The apostles and elders met to confer about this matter.
B044C015V007	44	15	7	After there had been much debate, Peter rose and said to them, "Brethren, you know that in early days God chose among you that through my mouth the Gentiles should hear the message of good news and should believe.
B044C015V008	44	15	8	And God, who knows all hearts, bore witness to them by giving them the Holy Spirit, just as he did to us.
B044C015V009	44	15	9	He made no difference between us and them in cleansing their hearts by faith.
B044C015V010	44	15	10	Now, therefore, why are you testing God by putting on the neck of the disciples a yoke which neither our fathers nor we have been able to bear?
B044C015V011	44	15	11	On the contrary we believe that we are saved through the grace of the Lord Jesus just as they are."
B044C015V012	44	15	12	The whole assembly remained silent and listened to Barnabas and Paul relating all the signs and wonders that God had done through them among the Gentiles.
B044C015V013	44	15	13	When they ceased speaking, James said, "Brethren, listen to me.
B044C015V014	44	15	14	Symeon has told how first God graciously visited the Gentiles and took a people for his name.
B044C015V015	44	15	15	With this the words of the prophets agree, as it is written,
B044C015V016	44	15	16	'After this I will return and build up again the tent of David which has fallen down; yes, I will build up its ruins and erect it again,
B044C015V017	44	15	17	that the rest of mankind may seek the Lord, even all the Gentiles upon whom my name has been bestowed, says the Lord
B044C015V018	44	15	18	who does these things foreknown from of old.'
B044C015V019	44	15	19	Therefore I judge best not to trouble those of the Gentiles who have turned to God,
B044C015V020	44	15	20	but to write to them to abstain from contamination with idols, and from unchastity, and from what has been strangled, and from blood.
B044C015V021	44	15	21	For Moses has had for generations past in every city those who preach him, for he is read in the synagogues every Sabbath."
B044C015V022	44	15	22	Then it seemed good to the apostles and the elders, with the whole church, to select men from themselves and to send them to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas; namely, Judas called Barsabbas, and Silas, men esteemed among the brethren.
B044C015V023	44	15	23	They wrote and sent by their hands the following letter: "The Apostles and the Brethren who are elders, to the Brethren from the Gentiles in Antioch and Syria and Cilicia: Greeting.
B044C015V024	44	15	24	"Inasmuch as we have heard that certain persons from us have troubled you with words, unsettling your minds, \'97 men whom we did not authorize, \'97
B044C015V025	44	15	25	it seemed good, after unanimous agreement, to select some men and send them to you with our beloved Barnabas and Paul,
B044C015V026	44	15	26	who have exposed their lives for the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B044C015V027	44	15	27	We have sent therefore Judas and Silas, who will tell you orally the same things.
B044C015V028	44	15	28	For it seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us to lay on you no further burden than these necessary things:
B044C015V029	44	15	29	to abstain from things sacrificed to idols, and from blood, and from strangled things, and from unchastity. If you keep yourselves from these you will do well. Farewell."
B044C015V030	44	15	30	So they were sent away and went down to Antioch, where they called together the whole body and delivered over the letter.
B044C015V031	44	15	31	On reading it they rejoiced over the encouragement.
B044C015V032	44	15	32	Both Judas and Silas, being themselves prophets, encouraged and confirmed the brethren by long addresses.
B044C015V033	44	15	33	After spending some time they were sent away with a message of peace from the brethren to those who had sent them.
B044C015V034	44	15	34	
        
B044C015V035	44	15	35	Paul and Barnabas stayed on in Antioch teaching and telling, in association with many others, the good news of the Lord's message.
B044C015V036	44	15	36	After some time Paul said to Barnabas, "Let us go back and visit the brethren in every city in which we made known the Lord's message, and see how they are prospering."
B044C015V037	44	15	37	Barnabas wished to take along John who was called Mark.
B044C015V038	44	15	38	But Paul did not approve of taking him along, since he had left them in Pamphylia and had not gone on with them into the work.
B044C015V039	44	15	39	Such a difference of feeling resulted that they separated from each other. Barnabas took Mark and sailed away to Cyprus.
B044C015V040	44	15	40	Paul selected Silas and left, after being commended to the grace of the Lord by the brethren.
B044C015V041	44	15	41	They went through Syria and Cilicia strengthening the churches.
B044C016V001	44	16	1	THEY came to Derbe and Lystra. At Lystra there was a disciple named Timothy, the son of a Jewish woman, who was a believer, and of a Greek father.
B044C016V002	44	16	2	He had a good reputation among the brethren in Lystra and Iconium.
B044C016V003	44	16	3	Paul wished to have Timothy go with him. So he took him and circumcised him because of the Jews who were in those parts. For they all knew that his father was a Greek.
B044C016V004	44	16	4	Thus they traveled through the cities and delivered to the disciples for observance the rules that had been decided on by the apostles and elders in Jerusalem.
B044C016V005	44	16	5	So the churches grew firmer in faith and increased in numbers from day to day.
B044C016V006	44	16	6	They went through Phrygia and the Galatian country, the Holy Spirit having prevented their speaking the message in Asia.
B044C016V007	44	16	7	Upon reaching Mysia they attempted to go into Bithynia, but the spirit of Jesus did not allow them.
B044C016V008	44	16	8	Passing by Mysia they came down to Troas.
B044C016V009	44	16	9	There a vision appeared to Paul in the night \'97 a Macedonian man was standing and begging him saying, "Come over into Macedonia and help us."
B044C016V010	44	16	10	After Paul had seen the vision, we at once tried to go out to Macedonia, inferring that God had called on us to tell the good news to the people there.
B044C016V011	44	16	11	Sailing away from Troas we made a straight run to Samothrace, and on the next day to Neapolis.
B044C016V012	44	16	12	From there we went to Philippi, which is the first city of that part of Macedonia and is a Roman colony. We remained in that city for a number of days.
B044C016V013	44	16	13	On the Sabbath day we went outside of the gate to a place on the riverside where it was customary to go for prayer, and we sat down and talked with the women who had gathered there.
B044C016V014	44	16	14	One woman named Lydia, a dealer in purple, from the city of Thyatira, who reverenced God, was listening. God opened her heart to receive what was said by Paul.
B044C016V015	44	16	15	When she had been baptized along with her household, she begged us, "If you have judged me to be faithful to the Lord, come into my house and stay," and she insisted on our doing so.
B044C016V016	44	16	16	It so happened that as we were going to the place of prayer a certain slave girl who had a spirit of divination met us. She was bringing great gain to her masters by divining.
B044C016V017	44	16	17	She followed Paul and us and kept calling out, "These men are servants of God Most High, and they are teaching you the way of salvation."
B044C016V018	44	16	18	This she kept doing for many days. Paul was annoyed, and turning he said to the spirit, "I tell you in the name of Jesus Christ to come out of her," and it came out at that very moment.
B044C016V019	44	16	19	When her masters saw that the hope of their gain was gone, they laid hold of Paul and Silas and dragged them into the public square before the authorities.
B044C016V020	44	16	20	Bringing them in, they said to the magistrates, "These men, who are Jews, are disturbing our city
B044C016V021	44	16	21	and teaching customs which it is not proper for us, who are Romans, to receive or practice."
B044C016V022	44	16	22	The crowd joined in the attack upon them, and the magistrates tore off their clothes and ordered them to be beaten with rods.
B044C016V023	44	16	23	After laying many stripes upon them they cast them into prison, ordering the jailer to keep them securely.
B044C016V024	44	16	24	He on receiving such an order thrust them into the inner prison and made their feet secure in the stocks.
B044C016V025	44	16	25	But about midnight Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and the other prisoners were listening.
B044C016V026	44	16	26	Suddenly there was a great earthquake, so that the foundations of the prison were shaken. Immediately all the doors were opened and every one's fetters were loosed.
B044C016V027	44	16	27	The jailer, waking from sleep and seeing the doors of the prison open, drew his sword and was about to kill himself, thinking that the prisoners had escaped.
B044C016V028	44	16	28	But Paul said with a loud voice, "Do no harm to yourself, for we are all here."
B044C016V029	44	16	29	Calling for a light he sprang in and fell down trembling before Paul and Silas,
B044C016V030	44	16	30	and led them out and said, "Men, what must I do to be saved?"
B044C016V031	44	16	31	They said, "Believe in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved, and your household,"
B044C016V032	44	16	32	and they told the message of God to him and to all who were in his house.
B044C016V033	44	16	33	He took them at that hour of the night and washed their stripes. Then he was baptized, he and all of his household, immediately.
B044C016V034	44	16	34	He brought them into his house and spread the table for them, and rejoiced with his whole family because he had believed in God.
B044C016V035	44	16	35	When morning came the magistrates sent their orderlies to say, "Set those men at liberty."
B044C016V036	44	16	36	The jailer told this order to Paul, "The magistrates have sent to have you set at liberty. Now go out and proceed on your journey in peace."
B044C016V037	44	16	37	But Paul said to them, "After beating us publicly and without a trial, although we are Romans, they cast us into prison. And are they now sending us out secretly? No, let them come themselves and lead us out."
B044C016V038	44	16	38	The orderlies reported these words to the magistrates. When they heard that they were Romans they were alarmed,
B044C016V039	44	16	39	and came and begged them, and after leading them out requested them to leave the city.
B044C016V040	44	16	40	They came out of the prison and went into Lydia's house, and after seeing and encouraging the brethren they departed.
B044C017V001	44	17	1	AFTER passing through Amphipolis and Apollonia they came to Thessalonica. Here there was a synagogue of the Jews.
B044C017V002	44	17	2	According to Paul's custom he went in to meet with them, and on three Sabbath days he reasoned with them from the Scriptures,
B044C017V003	44	17	3	explaining and showing that it was necessary that the Christ should suffer and rise from the dead, and saying, "Jesus of whom I am telling you is the Christ."
B044C017V004	44	17	4	Some of them were persuaded and attached themselves to Paul and Silas \'97 a large number of the pious Greeks and not a few of the leading women.
B044C017V005	44	17	5	But the Jews became excited and, taking with them some of the base loafers from the market-place, they made a mob and threw the city into confusion. They attacked the house of Jason and tried to bring Paul and Silas out to the people.
B044C017V006	44	17	6	Not finding them, they dragged Jason and certain brethren before the magistrates, shouting, "These men who have upset the world have now come here.
B044C017V007	44	17	7	Jason has received them. They all do contrary to the decrees of Caesar, saying that there is a different king \'97 Jesus."
B044C017V008	44	17	8	Both the crowd and the magistrates were disturbed on hearing this.
B044C017V009	44	17	9	So they took security from Jason and the rest and then dismissed them.
B044C017V010	44	17	10	The brethren immediately sent off Paul and Silas in the night to Beraea. They on arrival went into the synagogue of the Jews.
B044C017V011	44	17	11	These people were nobler than those in Thessalonica. They welcomed the message with all readiness and examined the Scriptures daily to see whether these things were so.
B044C017V012	44	17	12	Consequently many of them believed, and also not a few Greeks; women of high standing and men.
B044C017V013	44	17	13	When the Jews of Thessalonica learned that God's message had been proclaimed by Paul also in Beraea, they came there agitating and disturbing the crowds.
B044C017V014	44	17	14	At once then the brethren sent away Paul to go down to the sea coast. Silas and Timothy remained there.
B044C017V015	44	17	15	Those who were conducting Paul took him as far as Athens, and, after receiving a letter to Silas and Timothy to come to him as soon as possible, they left.
B044C017V016	44	17	16	While Paul was waiting for them in Athens, his spirit was stirred within him as he looked upon the city full of idols.
B044C017V017	44	17	17	He often debated in the synagogue with the Jews and pious persons, and in the market-place every day with whoever happened to be there.
B044C017V018	44	17	18	Some of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophers encountered him, and some said, "What can this idle talker mean?" Others said, "He seems to be a proclaimer of foreign gods," because he was telling the good news of Jesus and the resurrection.
B044C017V019	44	17	19	They took him and led him up on to the Areopagus, saying, "May we know what this new doctrine that you are speaking of is?
B044C017V020	44	17	20	For you are bringing strange and surprising things to our ears. We wish to know what these things are."
B044C017V021	44	17	21	For all the Athenians and the foreigners residing there spent their time in nothing else than in telling or hearing something newer than the last.
B044C017V022	44	17	22	Paul took his stand in the midst of the Areopagus and said: "Men of Athens, I see that you are in every way unusually reverential to the gods.
B044C017V023	44	17	23	For in passing about and contemplating your sacred objects I came upon an altar on which was inscribed, 'To an unknown God.' What you are worshiping in ignorance \'97 that I am making known to you.
B044C017V024	44	17	24	"The God who made the world and all the things that are in it, he who is Lord of heaven and earth, does not dwell in temples made by hands,
B044C017V025	44	17	25	nor is he served by human hands, as if he needed anything. For he gives to all life and breath and all things.
B044C017V026	44	17	26	And he made of one every nation of men to dwell on all the face of the earth, having marked out the appointed times and the boundaries of their abodes,
B044C017V027	44	17	27	that they might seek for God, if they could feel after him and find him, though, indeed, he is not far from each one of us.
B044C017V028	44	17	28	For in him we live and move and are; as some of your own poets have said, 'For we also are his offspring.'
B044C017V029	44	17	29	Being then the offspring of God, we ought not to think that deity is like gold or silver or stone, a thing carved by man's art and thought.
B044C017V030	44	17	30	The times of ignorance God overlooked, but now he commands all men everywhere to change,
B044C017V031	44	17	31	since he has set a day in which he will soon judge the world in justice by the man whom he has appointed, and of whom he has given evidence to all men by raising him from the dead."
B044C017V032	44	17	32	When they heard of the resurrection of the dead, some sneered; others said, "We will hear you again about this."
B044C017V033	44	17	33	So Paul went out from the midst of them.
B044C017V034	44	17	34	But certain men attached themselves to him and believed. Among them was Dionysius the Areopagite, and there was a woman named Damaris and several other persons.
B044C018V001	44	18	1	AFTER this Paul left Athens and came to Corinth.
B044C018V002	44	18	2	There he found a Jew named Aquila, born in Pontus but recently come from Italy with Priscilla his wife, because Claudius had ordered all Jews to leave Rome. Paul visited these people,
B044C018V003	44	18	3	and because he was of the same trade stayed with them and they worked together; for by trade they were tent-makers.
B044C018V004	44	18	4	But in the synagogue every Sabbath he reasoned and endeavored to persuade both Jews and Greeks.
B044C018V005	44	18	5	When Silas and Timothy came down from Macedonia, Paul was absorbed by the message, bearing witness to the Jews that Jesus was the Christ.
B044C018V006	44	18	6	When they resisted and spoke profane words, he rent his garments and said to them, "Your blood is on your own heads. I am clear, and from now on I am going to the Gentiles."
B044C018V007	44	18	7	So he changed over from there and came into the house of a man named Titus Justus, who reverenced God. His house was next to the synagogue.
B044C018V008	44	18	8	Crispus, the synagogue Director, believed in the Lord with all his household, and many of the Corinthians when they heard believed and were baptized.
B044C018V009	44	18	9	The Lord spoke in the night by a vision to Paul, 
B044C018V010	44	18	10	
        
B044C018V011	44	18	11	So he stayed a year and six months, teaching among them the message of God.
B044C018V012	44	18	12	While Gallio was Proconsul of Achaia, the Jews with one mind made an attack on Paul and brought him before the court,
B044C018V013	44	18	13	saying, "This man is inducing men to worship God in a way contrary to law."
B044C018V014	44	18	14	As Paul was about to open his mouth, Gallio said to the Jews, "If it was some crime or wicked knavery, O you Jews, I would have reasonable patience with you.
B044C018V015	44	18	15	But if it is a dispute about doctrine and names and your own law, see to it yourselves. I will not be a judge of these things,"
B044C018V016	44	18	16	and he drove them from before the judge's seat.
B044C018V017	44	18	17	Then they laid hold of Sosthenes, the synagogue Director, and beat him right in front of the judge's seat. But Gallio cared for none of these things.
B044C018V018	44	18	18	Paul remained a number of days more. Then after taking leave of the brethren he sailed away to Syria, and Priscilla and Aquila went with him. He had shaved his head at Cenchreae, for he had a vow.
B044C018V019	44	18	19	They came to Ephesus and Paul left his companions there. He himself went into the synagogue and debated with the Jews.
B044C018V020	44	18	20	Although they begged him to stay longer, he did not consent,
B044C018V021	44	18	21	but took his leave, saying, "I will return to you again, God willing."
B044C018V022	44	18	22	From Ephesus he put to sea and came to Caesarea. Then he went up 
B044C018V023	44	18	23	After spending some time there he set out and went through the Galatian country and Phrygia, place by place, strengthening all the disciples.
B044C018V024	44	18	24	A certain Jew named Apollos, an Alexandrian by birth, a learned man, had come to Ephesus.
B044C018V025	44	18	25	He was strong in knowledge of the Scriptures and had been instructed in the way of the Lord, and, being very earnest in spirit, was teaching accurately about Jesus, although he knew no baptism but John's.
B044C018V026	44	18	26	This man began to speak fearlessly in the synagogue. When Priscilla and Aquila heard him, they took him and explained to him the way of God more accurately still.
B044C018V027	44	18	27	As he wished to cross over to Achaia, the brethren encouraged him and wrote to the disciples to welcome him. So he went and greatly helped those who had believed through grace.
B044C018V028	44	18	28	For he powerfully and publicly refuted the Jews, showing from the Scriptures that Jesus is the Christ.
B044C019V001	44	19	1	WHILE Apollos was in Corinth, Paul, after passing through the upper country, came to Ephesus and found certain disciples.
B044C019V002	44	19	2	He said to them, "Did you receive the Holy Spirit when you believed?" They said to him, "On the contrary, we did not even hear that there was a Holy Spirit."
B044C019V003	44	19	3	He said, "How then were you baptized?" They said, "With John's baptism."
B044C019V004	44	19	4	Paul said, "John baptized with the baptism of a change of heart, telling the people to believe in one who was coming after him, that is, in Jesus."
B044C019V005	44	19	5	On hearing that, they were baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus,
B044C019V006	44	19	6	and when Paul laid his hands on them the Holy Spirit came on them and they spoke with tongues and prophesied.
B044C019V007	44	19	7	There were about twelve of these men in all.
B044C019V008	44	19	8	For three months Paul went into the synagogue and spoke fearlessly, arguing persuasively regarding the kingdom of God.
B044C019V009	44	19	9	When some were hardened and would not believe and spoke evil of the Way before the congregation, he departed from them and took away his disciples and discussed daily in the lecture-hall of Tyrannus.
B044C019V010	44	19	10	This went on for two years, so that all the inhabitants of Asia, both Jews and Greeks, heard the message of the Lord.
B044C019V011	44	19	11	Through the hands of Paul, God did miracles of no ordinary kind,
B044C019V012	44	19	12	so that handkerchiefs and aprons that had touched his body were carried to the sick, and the diseases left them and the evil spirits departed.
B044C019V013	44	19	13	Then some of the wandering Jewish exorcists undertook to invoke over those who had evil spirits the name of the Lord Jesus, saying, "I adjure you by Jesus whom Paul proclaims."
B044C019V014	44	19	14	There were seven sons of a certain Sceva, a Jewish high priest, who did this.
B044C019V015	44	19	15	But the evil spirit answered them, "Jesus I know and Paul I know; but who are you?"
B044C019V016	44	19	16	and the man in whom the evil spirit was sprang on them and overpowered both of them, and so belabored them that they fled from that house naked and wounded.
B044C019V017	44	19	17	This became known to all who were living in Ephesus, both Jews and Greeks, and awe fell on all of them, and the name of the Lord Jesus came to be held in high honor.
B044C019V018	44	19	18	Many of those who had become believers came confessing and telling of their practices.
B044C019V019	44	19	19	A number of those who had practiced magic brought their books and burned them before all. Adding up the prices of them they found the total to be fifty thousand pieces of silver.
B044C019V020	44	19	20	Thus vigorously the Lord's message grew and strengthened.
B044C019V021	44	19	21	When these things had been accomplished Paul took it in mind to pass through Macedonia and Achaia and go to Jerusalem, saying, "After I have been there I must see Rome also."
B044C019V022	44	19	22	He sent on into Macedonia two of his assistants, Timothy and Erastus, but he himself remained awhile in Asia.
B044C019V023	44	19	23	At that time there arose no small commotion about the Way.
B044C019V024	44	19	24	For a certain man named Demetrius, a silversmith, a maker of silver shrines of Artemis, was bringing to the artisans no small gain.
B044C019V025	44	19	25	He gathered these and the workmen employed about such things and said, "Men, you know that from this business we get our wealth,
B044C019V026	44	19	26	and you see and hear that not only at Ephesus, but also throughout almost all Asia this Paul has persuaded and drawn away a large number, saying that hand-made gods are not gods at all.
B044C019V027	44	19	27	Not only is this trade of ours in danger of coming into disrepute, but also the temple of the great goddess Artemis is in danger of being held of no account, and she whom now all Asia and the wide world worship will be deposed from her majesty."
B044C019V028	44	19	28	Upon hearing this, they became full of anger and shouted, "Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!"
B044C019V029	44	19	29	The city was filled with confusion, and the people rushed with one mind into the theater, having gotten hold of Gaius and Aristarchus, fellow travelers of Paul's.
B044C019V030	44	19	30	When Paul wished to go in and face the people the disciples would not let him.
B044C019V031	44	19	31	Some of the city officials who were his friends sent to him and begged him not to expose himself in the theater.
B044C019V032	44	19	32	Some were shouting one thing and some another, for the assembly was in confusion, and the most did not know why they had come together.
B044C019V033	44	19	33	Some of the crowd fixed on Alexander, since the Jews were putting him forward. And Alexander motioned with his hand and wished to make a defense before the people.
B044C019V034	44	19	34	But when they recognized that he was a Jew, there arose one shout from all for about two hours, "Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!"
B044C019V035	44	19	35	Then the City Clerk quieted the crowd and said, "Men of Ephesus, who is there of all men who does not know that the city of Ephesus is the temple-keeper of the great Artemis, and of her image which fell down from Zeus?
B044C019V036	44	19	36	Since these things are indisputable, you ought to be calm and do nothing rash.
B044C019V037	44	19	37	For you have brought here these men who are not robbers of temples nor defamers of your goddess.
